      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>Homer and Cortland are towns in Cortland County in Central New York. Both were part of the Central New York Military Tract. 
	  The town of Homer was established in 1794 and the village of Homer was incorporated in 1835.  
	  Cortland was settled in 1791 and incorporated as a village in 1853.</p>
	  <p>Hailed as a solution to the problem of stagecoaches, wagons and other transportation (both personal and commercial) 
	  bogging down in muddy roads during the rainy season, plank roads inspired an investment boom across the country in the late 
	  1840s.  The first plank road in the country was built in North Syracuse, New York to speed the transport of salt 
	  and other goods.  Unfortunately, despite millions of dollars in investments, plank roads did not fulfill their promise 
	  due to rapid deterioriation and high maintenance costs, and by 1900 the boom had become a bust.</p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Homer-Cortland Plank Road Minute Book</emph> is the minute book of the board of directors of the Homer-Cortland Plank Road, 
		 Cortland County, New York, covering operations of the road from notice of a meeting to open books for subscriptions to stock 
		 for its construction.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      
